#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:1
msgid "x86-64"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:3
msgid "Guidelines that apply only to x86-64 code under `ostd/src/arch/x86/`."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:5
msgid "Align the stack to 16 bytes before a call (`16b-align-rsp-before-call`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:7
msgid ""
"The System V AMD64 ABI requires `%rsp` to be 16-byte aligned at the point of "
"a `call`, so that the callee sees a 16-byte-aligned frame once the return "
"address is pushed. In hand-written assembly that calls into Rust or C, keep "
"`%rsp` 16-byte aligned immediately before each `call`: when an entry or trap "
"path has pushed an odd number of 8-byte values, push one more (a scratch "
"register, or a dummy) to restore the alignment."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:14
msgid ""
"A misaligned stack is undefined behavior — the Rust or C callee may use SSE "
"instructions such as `movaps` that fault on an unaligned operand."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-hardware/cpu-architecture-specific/x86-64.md:17
msgid ""
"See also: the [System V AMD64 ABI](https://gitlab.com/x86-psABIs/x86-64-ABI) "
"(§3.2.2, \"The Stack Frame\"); `ostd/src/arch/x86/trap/syscall.S`, which "
"pushes an extra register to keep `%rsp` aligned before calling into Rust."
msgstr ""
